So 1 has finitely many digits. Suppose n has finitely many digits. Does n+1 also have finitely many digits? If so, then all natural numbers have finitely many digits.
If not, then there is some finite number n such that n+1 is infinite.  In other words, there is a &quot;largest finite number.&quot;
It also depends on how you define infinite. Usually we say a number is &quot;infinite&quot; if it is &gt; every real number.  By that definition, no natural number is infinite, since all natural numbers are real numbers.

This doesn&#39;t mean we can take cardinal numbers and do normal arithmetic (such as subtraction) on them without knowing what sets we&#39;re talking about (this is okay because order on cardinalities is not defined by arithmetic).

But this idea of &quot;larger&quot; or &quot;smaller&quot; infinite sets can give us a more detailed description than just &quot;infinite.&quot;  

There are provable difference between infinite sets of different cardinalities, and these differences can be helpful in subjects like topology and analysis.

